      "solution": "#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main() {\n    int n;\n    float t = 0, r;\n    for (scanf(\"%d\", &n); n--; ) {\n        scanf(\"%f\", &r);\n        t = (t + r - 2 * t * r) / (1 - t * r);\n        if (t == 1) break;\n    }\n    printf(\"%.4f\\n\", t);\n}\n",
      "statement": "When {{z}} units of light shine on any side of a mirror with reflectivity {{r}}, {{rz}} units of light are reflected, and the other {{(1-r)z}} units of light pass through the mirror. \nThere are [[n]] mirrors numbered 1...[[n]] arranged in a row. Mirror [[i]] has reflectivity [[r_i]]. Find the total amount of light reflected back to the source when {{1}} unit of light shines on the first mirror. \nNote that light can be reflected multiple times.\n`----> | | | | |\nlight 1 2 3 4 5 ...`",
